article.description:
Rookie Tamika Catchings had 24 points and 10
rebounds to lead the Indiana Fever to a 68-57 victory over
Cleveland on Monday night, handing the Rockers their fourth
consecutive defeat.
article.headline: Indiana hopes to take advantage of home schedule
article.linkText: Catchings gets Indiana turned around at home
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Rookie Tamika Catchings had 24 points and 10
rebounds to lead the Indiana Fever to a 68-57 victory over
Cleveland on Monday night, handing the Rockers their fourth
consecutive defeat.

	   Catchings, who was named a starter for the Eastern Conference
All-Stars on Sunday, was 7-for-15 from the field, including 4-for-7
from 3-point range, and 6-for-8 from the free-throw line.

	   Bridget Pettis added 11 points for the Fever (8-9) in the opener
of an eight-game homestand.

	   ''After June, we need to win these home games,'' Catchings said
of Indiana, which played seven of its last nine games in June on
the road, and traveled to Orlando on July 3 before returning to
Conseco Fieldhouse. ''Just being on the road all of June, we didn't
get the record we wanted. That makes winning these home games all
the more important.''

	   Penny Taylor and Merlakia Jones each scored 12 points for the
Rockers (6-11).

	   Catchings had a four-point play with 14:19 remaining that gave
Indiana a 48-36 lead. She hit a 3-pointer from 22 feet, was fouled
by Mery Andrade and made the free throw.

	   ''We were going through a little bit of a drought there, so I
wanted to get a basket,'' Catchings said. ''I was saying, 'Please
go in,' because I didn't know if it was a good shot or a bad shot.
I think I might have had one of those in high school, but it's been
a long time.''

	   Taylor scored eight points in a 12-2 run shortly that brought
Cleveland to 54-51 with 7:16 remaining. But backup center Kelly
Schumacher hit two free throws and Catchings drove the lane for a
basket, was fouled and hit the free throw to give the Fever a 59-51
lead with 6:12 remaining.

	   By halftime, Indiana led 36-20 and Catchings had 13 points and
seven rebounds.

	   ''That's Tamika. She's been doing that all year,'' Fever coach
Nell Fortner said. ''We're still in the thick of this in the East.
People know we've got to step up, and that's what they did tonight.

	   ''Bridget Pettis came up big, especially in the first half. I
thought Kelly Schumacher really stepped up tonight, too. That was
important.''

	   When starting center Olympia Scott-Richardson got into foul
trouble, Schumacher came in to score eight points and add four
rebounds.

	   Rockers head coach Dan Hughes said Catchings was the
difference.

	   ''She's physical, big, strong, and she can shoot the 3,'' he
said. ''They used her at the third and fourth spot, so she pulled
our big players out.''
